+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+
| **The Key Insight --- Why Installing a Root Certificate Grants Total  |
| Decryption**                                                          |
|                                                                       |
| Your browser trusts hundreds of Root CAs by default --- Mozilla,      |
| Google, Microsoft, Comodo, DigiCert, government CAs in multiple       |
| countries. **Any of these can issue a valid certificate for any       |
| domain.** When you install ZAP\'s root certificate, you are adding    |
| ZAP to that list. ZAP can then sign a certificate for **any** site    |
| --- bbc.co.uk, your bank, your email provider --- and your browser    |
| will show a padlock for all of them.                                  |
|                                                                       |
| **This is not a flaw in TLS.** It is how TLS is designed. The padlock |
| means: \"this connection is encrypted and the certificate was issued  |
| by a CA your browser trusts.\" It does not mean: \"this connection    |
| cannot be intercepted.\" **HTTPS security is only as strong as the    |
| weakest CA in your trust store.**                                     |
